The major earthquake that struck the San Francisco Bay area Tuesday occurred in a region 
targeted from previous studies by seismologists as having the highest probability of a strong 
quake in North California. The quake's magnitude as 6.9 on the Richter scale and centered in the 
Santa Cruz, CA area 75 miles south of San Francisco.

Initial reports indicated widespread damage from the quake, especially affecting highways and 
old masonry buildings. It could serve as an engineering study for any possible damage in the Los 
Angles region, which has similar construction and a higher probability of a major quake 
occurring.</SUM>

<SUM
DOCSET="d077"
TYPE="PERDOC"
SIZE="100"
DOCREF="AP891017-0199"
SELECTOR="B"
SUMMARIZER="G">

A violent earthquake registering 6.9 on the Richter scale rocked Northern California Tuesday at 
5:04 pm. One report said the quake was centered near Hollister, 80 miles southeast of San 
Francisco in San Benito County. It was felt as far away as Reno NV, 225 miles southeast.

The extent of the damage was not immediately clear. A section of both the San Francisco Bridge 
and the Oakland-San Francisco Bridge collapsed. A building and a bridge in downtown Hollister 
collapsed. A major fire was burning in San Francisco's Marina District. World Series fans in 
Candlestick Park were terrified as the stands swayed.</SUM>

<SUM
DOCSET="d077"
TYPE="PERDOC"
SIZE="100"
DOCREF="AP891017-0195"
SELECTOR="B"
SUMMARIZER="G">

A major earthquake lasting about fifteen seconds and measuring 6.5 on the Richter scale, rocked 
northern California on Tuesday evening. One section of the San Francisco Bay Bridge collapsed. 
Nearby buildings swayed several feet and some may have collapsed. Phones and power were 
knocked out.

Fans at Candlestick Park waiting for the World Series to begin screamed as the stadium swayed 
for about fifteen seconds. Fans were evacuated and there were reports of some injuries.  

The quake shook buildings in Sacramento, 95 miles to the northeast, and was felt as far away as 
Reno, NV, 225 miles to the east.</SUM>

<SUM
DOCSET="d077"
TYPE="PERDOC"
SIZE="100"
DOCREF="AP891018-0084"
SELECTOR="B"
SUMMARIZER="G">

Ever since the 1906 earthquake devastated San Francisco, many scientists believed the next "big 
one" would strike the Los Angles area. Their studies gave various interpretations of how much 
stress was released by the 1906 earthquake (magnitude 8.3). The greater the quake, the more 
stress it relieves and, thus, the longer it takes for the same size quake to occur again. In the face 
of conflicting evidence, the US Geological Survey issued a 1988 report that concluded the 1906 
quake didn't release as much stress in the San Francisco region as believed. The 6.9 quake 
Tuesday confirmed the USGS study.</SUM>

<SUM
DOCSET="d077"
TYPE="PERDOC"
SIZE="100"
DOCREF="LA101889-0066"
SELECTOR="B"
SUMMARIZER="G">

Tuesday's earthquake, the strongest on the San Andreas fault since the 1906 San Francisco 
quake, came in a place scientists identified in 1988 as the most likely in Northern California 
within the next 30 years. The 1988 report cited probabilities for major temblors along the San 
Andreas in central and southern California, but pinpointed the Santa Cruz mountains as the most 
vulnerable partly because the area marked the southernmost point of maximum ground slippage 
during the 1906 earthquake. Pressure was probably building up in the neighboring southern 
segment of the San Andreas, which had not slipped as much since 1906.</SUM>

<SUM
DOCSET="d077"
TYPE="PERDOC"
SIZE="100"
DOCREF="AP891019-0037"
SELECTOR="B"
SUMMARIZER="G">

Private groups and officials from around the world and the US offered earthquake relief to the 
San Francisco Bay area. Los Angles shipped doctors, sonic equipment, and fire investigators; 
Charleston, SC and a California brewery sent drinking water; the Salvation Army provided 
cooked food canteens; the Red Cross blood units and shelters; and the Coast Guard boats and 
helicopters.

Britain flew in engineers. Israel and France offered search teams, and Osaka, Japan sent $10,000 
in cash. President Bush directed $273 million in aid but federal and private coffers, especially the 
Red Cross, are strained by previous responses to Hurricane Hugo.</SUM>

<SUM
