DOCREF="LA101889-0108"
SELECTOR="B"
SUMMARIZER="G">

Experience of a reporter at Candlestick Park for the World Series the night of the 1989 San 
Francisco quake:

I was sitting in a trailer outside the stadium when the earthquake hit. I looked out and the 
stadium was shaking. A special concrete joint on top of the stadium was opening and closing like 
cardboard. A few people were running out. I walked into the stadium to interview fans and 
sensed little panic. Most people stayed, waiting to hear whether the game would be postponed. 
When leaving, those in the upper deck seemed more shaken that those in lower levels.</SUM>

<SUM
DOCSET="d077"
TYPE="PERDOC"
SIZE="100"
DOCREF="LA102089-0172"
SELECTOR="B"
SUMMARIZER="G">

In the recent San Francisco earthquake, why did some luxury four-story apartments or office 
buildings collapse while high-rises escaped virtually unscathed? Accordingly, some buildings 
collapsed because of two things: very poor soil and very poor structural design. Some were built 
over landfill and others were erected earlier when there were no earthquake codes.

Four-story buildings with garages underneath have no walls on one side. Connections break and 
the front falls. Skyscrapers usually survive because architects factor in wind gusts and earth 
movement. In smaller buildings, contractors make sure that vertical forces--such as snow and 
ice--cannot force a collapse.</SUM>

<SUM
DOCSET="d077"
TYPE="PERDOC"
SIZE="100"
DOCREF="LA102089-0177"
SELECTOR="B"
SUMMARIZER="G">

A California Safety Commissioner said, "I've been wandering around San Francisco and it's like 
the blind man trying to feel an elephant. We're just now figuring out bits and pieces of this 
disaster."

A schoolteacher said, "Usually earthquakes pass but this one went on and on. It just wouldn't 
stop, it was very, very bad."

A woman driving toward San Francisco said, "At first I thought the smoke was fog. Then I could 
see a ball of flame."

A reporter covering the World Series at Candlestick Park noted, "The upper deck was absolutely 
shaking, the light stanchions were blowing back and forth."</SUM>

<SUM
DOCSET="d077"
TYPE="PERDOC"
SIZE="100"
DOCREF="LA102389-0075"
SELECTOR="B"
SUMMARIZER="G">

The cities of Charleston, SC and San Francisco have similarities and differences when they were 
the scenes of two back-to-back disasters: Hurricane Hugo and the Bay Area earthquake. 
Charleston had warning but San Francisco did not. Charleston's neighborhoods were littered 
with debris, 80% of the buildings were damaged, and power was out. San Francisco's streets 
were passable within a day and power was restored overnight.  Charleston, however, in contrast 
to San Francisco, could quickly assess structural damage and it lost no major economic area such 
as the Bay Bridge. Both have experienced delays in disaster relief from the federal government.</SUM>
